For Questions 1-2 you will be using the dataset
`data.nbds.veg.temp.water.txt` available on Canvas. This dataset
contains temperature and vegetation values for 120 Philadelphia
neighborhoods. There is also a categorical variable that indicates
whether each neighborhood is near or far from a large body of water
(river, creek or lake).

### Question 1 (25 points)

Fit a linear regression model with temperature as the outcome variable
and two predictor variables: vegetation and an indicator variable for
near vs. far from water. Also include an intercept in the model. Obtain
posterior samples and provide histograms, posterior means and 95%
posterior intervals for all unknown parameters in the model.

```{r}
#| label: Q1 EDA 
#| echo: FALSE

data.nbds <- read.table("data.nbds.veg.temp.water.txt", sep = ",", header = TRUE)
view(data.nbds)
```

```{r}
#| label: Q1 lm

lmTemp <- lm(temperature~vegetation + water.ind, data = data.nbds)
summary(lmTemp)
```

Both having more vegetation and being near water is *inversely*
correlated with higher temperature. The intercept is estimated to be
99.5961.

```{r}
beta.hat <- lmTemp$coef
p <- length(beta.hat)
n <- nrow(data.nbds)

s2 <- (n - p) * summary(lmTemp)$sigma^2
V.beta <- summary(lmTemp)$cov.unscaled
numsamp <- 1000

sigsq.samp <- 1 / rgamma(numsamp, shape = (n - p) / 2, rate = s2 / 2)

base_draws <- mvrnorm(numsamp, mu = rep(0, p), Sigma = V.beta)
scaled_draws <- base_draws * sqrt(sigsq.samp)

beta.samp <- sweep(scaled_draws, 2, beta.hat, "+")

postmean.beta <- apply(beta.samp, 2, mean)
postmean.sigsq <- mean(sigsq.samp)
```

```{r}
#| echo: false

print("Posterior Means (Intercept, Vegetation, Water.ind):")
print(postmean.beta)
print("Posterior Mean for Sigma^2:")
print(postmean.sigsq)
```

```{r}
allsamples <- cbind(beta.samp, sigsq.samp)
allsamples.sort <- apply(allsamples, 2, sort)

lower <- allsamples.sort[25,]
upper <- allsamples.sort[975,]

post.intervals.95 <- cbind(lower, upper)
row.names(post.intervals.95) <- c("beta.0", "beta.veg", "beta.water", "sigsq")
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
