Because I used a *non-informative prior*, the Bayesian posterior mean
and the Frequentist OLS estimate are mathematically identical for the
$\beta$ parameters (the PDF rendering is a little wobbly, but that is an
artifact). However, for $\sigma^2$ the Inverse-Gamma distribution is
right-skewed because variance can never be negative. The few larger
values in the long right tail pull the average to the right, slightly
away from the peak, it is about about 1.7% higher than our frequentist
estimates.

### Question 2 (25 points)

#### a. Consider a new Philadelphia neighborhood with vegetation $=0.6$ that is far from water.

Obtain posterior predictive samples for the temperature in this
neighborhood and provide the posterior mean and 95% posterior predictive
interval from your samples.

$$(\beta_0 \times 1) + (\beta_{veg} \times 0.6) + (\beta_{water} \times 0)$$

```{r}
Xstar_a <- c(1, 0.6, 0)

mu_star_a <- beta.samp %*% Xstar_a

ystar_samp_a <- rnorm(numsamp, mean = mu_star_a, sd = sqrt(sigsq.samp))

postmean_a <- mean(ystar_samp_a)
post_int_a <- quantile(ystar_samp_a, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
print(paste("Posterior Mean:", round(postmean_a, 4)))
print("95% Predictive Interval:")
print(post_int_a)
```

#### b. Now consider a new Philadelphia neighborhood with same vegetation $=0.6$ but that is near to water.

Obtain posterior predictive samples for the temperature in this
neighborhood and provide the posterior mean and 95% posterior predictive
interval from your samples. Compare with the interval that you
calculated in 2a.

$$(\beta_0 \times 1) + (\beta_{veg} \times 0.6) + (\beta_{water} \times 1)$$

```{r}
Xstar_b <- c(1, 0.6, 1)

mu_star_b <- beta.samp %*% Xstar_b

ystar_samp_b <- rnorm(numsamp, mean = mu_star_b, sd = sqrt(sigsq.samp))

postmean_b <- mean(ystar_samp_b)
post_int_b <- quantile(ystar_samp_b, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))
```

```{r}
#| echo: false

print(paste("Posterior Mean:", round(postmean_b, 4)))
print("95% Predictive Interval:")
print(post_int_b)
```

When comparing the two new neighborhoods, the predicted temperature for
the neighborhood near water is cooler than the neighborhood far from
water (Question 2a).

Specifically, the posterior predictive mean drops from roughly 88.09 to
86.15, and the entire 95% predictive interval shifts downward by
approximately 2 degrees. This shift aligns with the model's water
predictor coefficient estimated in Question 1. However, while the
intervals are centered at different temperatures, the overall width of
both predictive intervals remains almost identical (roughly 6.5 degrees
wide). This is because the model assumes the same underlying $\sigma^2$
and uncertainty for both predictions, regardless of their proximity to
water

